<BR><BR><BR><BR>
In Ghana, traditional music is often composed in call-and-response
form.  The lead drummer plays one phrase and the supporting drums play
an answer, creating a
<A HREF = "vuGbe.html"><I>vu gbe</I>, or drum language</A>,
conversation.  Human vocal songs in Ghana, and in the
African-American  diaspora, are often composed in the same form. 
<P>
In "Tele", the call-and-response form is combined with Andruid's
percussive poetry technique.  Percussive poetry is performance in
which spoken words are delivered with well-defined rhythms.  Voices
interlock musically, perhaps with other instrumentation, to form a
complete musical statement.  Click on the picture below to hear an
excerpt. 
<BR><BR><BR><BR>
<A HREF="sound/cantReach.au"><CENTER>
<IMG BORDER=2  HEIGHT=304 WIDTH=432 SRC="CHAINSImages/tele/telecute.jpeg">
